  "notes": [
    {
      "title": "Hamzated Verbs (الفعل المهموز)",
      "titleArabic": "الفعل المهموز",
      "content": [
        "Hamzated verbs (الفعل المهموز) have a hamza (ء) as one of their root letters. They follow regular conjugation patterns but have some spelling variations.",
        "The hamza can appear as the first radical (أَكَلَ), second radical (سَأَلَ), or third radical (قَرَأَ)."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "First radical hamza: أَكَلَ (to eat), أَخَذَ (to take), أَمَرَ (to command)",
        "Second radical hamza: سَأَلَ (to ask)",
        "Third radical hamza: قَرَأَ (to read)",
        "Conjugation follows regular patterns",
        "In some forms, hamza may change form (أ، ؤ، ئ، ء)"
      ],
      "examples": [
        { "arabic": "أَكَلَ الطَّعَامَ", "english": "He ate the food" },
        { "arabic": "سَأَلَ أُسْتَاذَهُ", "english": "He asked his teacher" },
        { "arabic": "قَرَأْتُ الْقُرْآنَ", "english": "I read the Quran" },
        { "arabic": "أَمَرَنَا اللهُ", "english": "Allah commanded us" }
      ]
    },
    {
      "title": "Imperatives of Hamzated Verbs",
      "titleArabic": "أمر الفعل المهموز",
      "content": [
        "When forming imperatives from verbs with hamza as the first radical, the initial hamza is often dropped."
      ],
      "keyPoints": [
        "أَكَلَ → كُلْ (Eat!)",
        "أَخَذَ → خُذْ (Take!)",
        "أَمَرَ → مُرْ (Command!)",
        "The second radical's vowel determines the imperative form"
      ]
    }
  ],
